@acnestudios’ 1981 jeans lean into a “lived-in” fantasy that feels more living room than street.⁠
⁠
The distressing reads like floral upholstery worn thin by time, soft, familiar, and slightly surreal, turning the jeans into something closer to memory than garment. They're currently available on Acne Studios' online shop for $950 USD.

@commedesgarcons and @bape_japan are titans of Japanese fashion, each shaping global style in totally different ways — CDG through avant-garde runway rebellion, BAPE through loud, culture-defining streetwear. They’ve been collaborating on and off since 2012, with a steady run of drops since 2020 when BAPE set up inside CDG’s Osaka flagship. The pieces are exactly what you’d expect: logo-heavy hoodies, striped shirts with Ape heads, and now even jorts, all remixing their signature styles into something fresh but familiar.⁠
⁠
So why isn’t it louder? Simple: scarcity. These collections are mostly sold at a single store in Japan, keeping them under the radar despite the hype-worthy formula. It also leans more BAPE than CDG’s experimental side, but with Y2K streetwear surging again, that’s hardly a downside. If this collab ever went global, it wouldn’t stay quiet for long.

@JacobAndCo. unveils the Godfather II, a $440,000 musical timepiece that brings cinema to the wrist.
Drawing inspiration from one of film’s most iconic sagas, the watch integrates two legendary compositions — The Godfather’s Waltz and The Godfather Love Theme — played through an intricate, built-in music box.
Encased in a sculpted Art Deco-inspired design, the piece combines horological artistry with cinematic storytelling. A flying tourbillon, dual power reserves, and a newly engineered movement elevate both its technical and aesthetic appeal, while the dial features a finely detailed portrait of Don Corleone alongside subtle references to the film’s legacy.
Limited to just 74 pieces, in tribute to the 1974 release of The Godfather Part II, the timepiece stands as a rare collector’s creation, where music, craftsmanship, and heritage converge.
@JacobAndCo #JacobAndCo

Kendall Jenner has sparked renewed interest in classic supercars after featuring a Ferrari 512 TR in a recent Instagram post. The appearance of the vintage model quickly gained traction online, drawing attention from both automotive enthusiasts and collectors.
An evolution of the Testarossa, the 512 TR represents Ferrari’s analog era, combining its signature design with performance-focused refinements. Its resurgence in popular culture reflects a broader shift toward appreciating classic V12 models, as demand grows for heritage-driven cars over modern, tech-heavy alternatives.
@kendalljenner #Luxurious
